Assume \( n \) is an even natural number. By definition, \( n \) is even if there exists an integer \( m \) such that \( n = 2m \). 

Since \( m \) is an integer and \( n \) is a natural number, we also have that \( m \) must be a non-negative integer (i.e., \( m \geq 0 \)), as the product of 2 and any negative integer would result in a negative integer, which contradicts the assumption that \( n \) is a natural number.

Thus, set \( k = m \). Then \( k \) is a natural number (as \( m \geq 0 \)) and we have \( n = 2k \), which completes the proof.
